Processing of SP3 binding data in different conditions

Description

This file contains the code for processing the search and quantification output files from the examination of the performance of SP3 when working with different binding conditions (e.g.incubation times and rinsing methods). These data were used to make portions of Figure XXXXX.

  • MGF files were generated using RawQuant.
  • The data were searched using SearchCLI and PeptideShakerCLI.
  • Raw files were parsed for quantification data with RawQuant.

Analysis

First call the libraries that are required.

#library(Biostrings)
library(Rmisc)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(cowplot)
library(tidyr)
#library(reshape)
library(data.table)
library(UpSetR)
#library(stringr)
#library(Peptides)

First thing we want to do is compile the identifications data into a usable object for plotting. This involves taking the output from PeptideShaker and combining it with the RawQuant data. This is carried out using the code below.

Incubation time data set

First I want to look at the incubation time data. Locate the input files for identifications and quantification.

id_files = list.files('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/binding-testing/reports-output', pattern='.*Duration.*Default_PSM_Report.txt',full.names=TRUE) #psm files 
quant_files = list.files('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/binding-testing/quant-output', pattern='.*Duration.*MS2ParseData.txt',full.names=TRUE) #ms2 files

Read in the identification data into a single data frame object.

id_parsed = data.frame() #identification data storage object
#iterate over the identification files 
for (i in 1:length(id_files)){
  psm_in = read.table(id_files[i],header=TRUE,sep='\t') #input file
  psm_f1 = psm_in %>% 
    dplyr::select(Protein.s., Sequence, Spectrum.File, Spectrum.Title, m.z, Identification.Charge) %>% #select columns
    dplyr::mutate(Spectrum.Title, scan_num = sub(".*?spectrum (.*?)", "\\1", Spectrum.Title)) %>% #parse out the scan number
    dplyr::mutate(Identification.Charge, id_charge = gsub("[^0-9]", "", Identification.Charge)) %>% #parse out the charge
    dplyr::mutate(Spectrum.Title, fraction = sub(".*?100p_(.*?)_[0-9]_MGF\\.mgf", "\\1", Spectrum.File)) %>% #parse the fraction
    dplyr::mutate(Spectrum.Title, replicate = sub(".*?min_(.*?)_MGF\\.mgf", "\\1", Spectrum.File)) %>% #parse the replicate
    dplyr::select(Protein.s., Sequence, scan_num, m.z, id_charge, fraction, replicate) %>% #select new columns
    dplyr::mutate(Protein.s., first_accession = sapply(strsplit(as.character(Protein.s.),"\\,"), `[`, 1)) #parse the accession
  #adjust the column names
  colnames(psm_f1) = c('accession_groups','sequence','ScanNumber','id_precursor_mz','id_charge','fraction','replicate','accession')
  psm_f2 = dplyr::filter(psm_f1, !grepl('CONT_', accession_groups)) #remove the contaminant proteins
  id_parsed = rbind(id_parsed,psm_f2) #group the data with the previously processed set
}

Now we can process the rawquant data for the intensity values.

quant_parsed = data.frame()
#iterate over the rawquant files
for (i in 1:length(quant_files)){
  quant_in = read.table(quant_files[i],header=TRUE,sep='\t') #input file
  quant_in$fraction = sub(".*?100p_(.*?)_[0-9]_MS2ParseData\\.txt", "\\1", quant_files[i]) #parse out the fraction
  quant_in$replicate = sub(".*?min_(.*?)_MS2ParseData\\.txt", "\\1", quant_files[i]) #parse out the replicate
  quant_parsed = rbind(quant_parsed, quant_in) #combine with the previous data
}

Now we can combine the two data sets together using a simple merge and save the data.

id_quant = merge(id_parsed, quant_parsed, by=c('ScanNumber', 'fraction', 'replicate'))
saveRDS(id_quant, '/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/binding-testing/Routput/ch_feb2018_SP3-binding-incubation-time_id-quant-all.rds') #save the data

Now plot the data in a boxplot.

incubation_plot = ggplot(peptide_subset, aes(fraction, log10(PrecursorMaxIntensity),group=interaction(replicate,fraction))) +
    #geom_point(aes(fill=fraction),position=position_jitterdodge(dodge.width=0.9),colour='grey60',alpha=0.1) +

    labs(x = "sample", y = 'peptide intensity', title = 'sp3 incubation times') +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 9)) +
    #scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,1.5e9)) +
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    scale_fill_manual(values=brewer.pal(6,"Set3")[c(1,3:4)]) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,10), breaks = seq(0,10,1))
incubation_plot #call the plot
save_plot('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/binding-testing/Routput/ch_feb2018_SP3-binding-incubation-time_peptide-boxplot.pdf',incubation_plot)

This looks goodbut it doesnt tell me anything about recovery of identical peptides across the incubation times. For this we could use a correlation. Calculate and plot the correlation in intensities between a pair of replicate samples.

peptide_wide = spread(peptide_subset, fraction, PrecursorMaxIntensity) #convert to wide format
cor(peptide_wide[,3:5],method = 'pearson')
          10min     20min      5min
10min 1.0000000 0.9250320 0.9455061
20min 0.9250320 1.0000000 0.9230528
5min  0.9455061 0.9230528 1.0000000
#so the correlation is very nice here. Can state these values in the text, but make one plot as a display.
colnames(peptide_wide) = c('sequence','replicate','t10min','t20min','t5min')
incubation_corplot = ggplot(peptide_wide, aes(log10(t5min), log10(t10min))) +
    geom_point(colour='grey60',alpha=0.2,size=2) +  
    geom_smooth(method='lm',color='red') +
    labs(x = "5-minute incubation", y = '10-minute incubation', title = 'sp3 incubation times') +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 9)) +
    #scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,1.5e9)) +
    theme(legend.position="none")
incubation_corplot #call the plot
save_plot('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/binding-testing/Routput/ch_feb2018_SP3-binding-incubation-time-5v10min_peptide-scatter.pdf',incubation_corplot)

Mixing and rinsing methods data set

Now I will move on to the incubation type data (e.g.mixing, rinsing) and perform the same analysis. Locate the input files for identifications and quantification.

id_files = list.files('/projects/ptx_analysis/chughes/projects-current/sp3-follow-up/binding-testing/reports-output', pattern='.*Binding.*Default_PSM_Report.txt',full.names=TRUE) #psm files

Read in the identification data into a single data frame object
